Date: Sun, 29 Jun 1997 07:58:54 +0100
From: O. Hotz de Baar <Oz@upthorpe.demon.co.uk>

[Simon Elliot's message implies that VTEC's are rather common in the
environment and livestock are inevitably regularly exposed. Note that in a
country like the UK, with extensive rights of way across farmland and many
pet dogs, this extends to a very much greater number than just those working
directly with cattle. Indeed it would extend to most rural dwellers as well
as city dwellers who regularly walk in the countryside.
It will also be absurd that laboratories designed to handle pathogens
cannot handle VTEC's but the above mentioned groups do so regularly in an
uncontrolled manner. It is even more absurd when you consider that
establishments with facilities to perform animal studies probably have
VTEC's wild in their animal areas, let alone if they have an associated
farm surrounding the site.
The comment on funding is appropriate. It appears to have become common
practice in the UK for researchers to obtain funding by persuing a scare
campaign in the UK press. Personally I find this unethical. The stress (in
the UK) has been entirely on urban dwellers consuming meat products, and
those living in rural areas have been entirely ignored despite clearly
having a very much greater likelihood of exposure.
The increasing incidence of vegetables being responsible for the spread of
VTEC's outside the UK has singularly failed to enter the UK press which is
strange [The failure or the press? -- Mod CHC. Indeed, I have doubts that
the UK authorities are even aware that vegetables are a known carrier of
VTEC's.
I suspect your plea [to reassess the concept of infectious dose of VTEC and
how we communicate the dangers of this organism to the public and our funding
bodies will fall on deaf ears.
---
O. Hotz de Baar
Farmer
Southern England, UK.
