Date: Mon, June 30, 1997
From: Paul Goldwater <pgoldwat@medicine.adelaide.edu.au>
A couple of points raised by Dr Elliott deserve comment: His thesis in
favour of a high infectious dose of VTEC/SLTEC is not consistent with the
evidence. The Adelaide O111 epidemic showed that SLTEC O111 was present in
some samples of fermented sausage (mettwurst) in such small numbers that
immunomagnetic enrichment was required to show their presence. Probing
cultures of the incriminated mettwurst by PCR showed Stx sequences present in
7 of 16 samples and PCR for O111-specific sequences was positive in only 3 of
these. Isolates of SLTEC O111 were obtained in two of these three and in one
of the two & only after immunomagnetic bead enrichment.
There is now ample evidence of person-to-person transmission of EHEC in child
care settings (Belongia EA et al JAMA; 1993269: 883-888., Lerman Y etal. J
Clin Microbiol 1992; 30: 520-521., Samadpour M et al. J Clin Microbiol 1993:
31: 3179-3183., Spika JS et al. J Pediatr 1986; 109: 287-291., Reida P et al.
Int J Microbiol Virol Parasitol Infect Dis 1994: 281: 534-543); in families
(Lopez EL et al. J Pediatr 1992; 120: 210-215., Neill MA et al. Pediatrics
1987; 80: 37-40., Ostroff SM et al. JAMA 1989; 262: 355-359., Rowe PC et al.
J Pediatr 1994; 124: 21-26., Ratnam S et al. NEJM 1986; 315: 1612-1613.,
Spika JS et al. J Pediatr 1986; 109: 287-291., Banatvala N et al. Pediatr
Infect Dis J 1996; 15: 1008-1011.); in nursery school (Boudailliez B et al.
Pediatr Nephrol 1997; 11: 36-39); and in nursing homes (Carter AO et al. NEJM
1987; 317: 1496-1500., Ryan C et al. J Infect Dis 1986; 154: 631-637).
---
Paul N. Goldwater, FRACP, FRCPA
Microbiology and Infectious Diseases Department,
Women's & Children's Hospital,
North Adelaide,
South Australia 5006.
[4
Date: Mon, 30 Jun 1997
From: Andre Burnens <andre.burnens@vbi.unibe.ch>
The VTEC organism is probably considered too dangerous by most scientists for
human challenge experiments. However, there are indirect measures of low
infectious doses for pathogens. I consider bacteria showing all of the
following:
- evidence for person to person spread
- evidence for waterborne transmission
- evidence for laboratory-acquired infections
to show most certainly a low infectious dose. All modes of transmission have
been described for E. coli O157.
Calculating observed attack rates vs. infectious dose in foodborne outbreaks
where estimates of CFU/g for the pathogen in food is available could be used
to calculate approximate ID-50 values without need for human volunteer
experiments.

In Switzerland, VTEC are indeed very prevalent in cattle (in the range of
30 % or more). However, none of over 300 strains isolated from cattle in
our lab so far belongs to the O157 serogroup. I am not aware of any
published work showing E. coli O157 to be very prevalent in cattle. It is
true that the clinical (and public health) significance of non-O157 remain
to be established, for individual patients as well as their possible
presence in food.
There are three reports (the one below plus Philips G and Old DC, J-Hosp-
Infect (1997) 35:72, and Rao GG et al., J-Hosp-Infect (1996) 33:228-30) in
the literature on laboratory-acquired infections with E. coli O157. The one
we reported (Burnens AP et al., Int-J-Med-Microbiol (1993) 279:512-517) did
not involve any unusual incident, however, the strain was used in a 'research
setting' which may involve more risks than exposure in a diagnostic
laboratory. Given the rarity of the pathogen in Switzerland (two strains
reported per year), the single case of an infected laboratory worker
nevertheless makes the infectiousness of the E. coli O157 look impressive.
---
Andre Burnens
[5
Date: Mon, 30 Jun 1997
From: Jim Koopman <jkoopman@sph.umich.edu>
Simon Elliott, in a recent posting on VTEC, states that "The theoretical
infectious dose for ANY organism is 1 but the infectious dose follows a
probability curve." The specific theory under which that holds was not
stated. I would think any such theory must be highly impropable. It
would have to hold that the reproduction number of an organism in a host
(the number of next generation organisms that each organism generates)
is independent of the number of other organisms in the environment
which can absorb immune response elements that could kill an organism.
The theoretical infectious dose should be that number of organisms where
the average reproduction number is able to sustain the organism density
in the original dose.
---
Jim Koopman MD MPH Phone (313) 763-5629 office
